I think possibly because he, too, is wrong.

1234
01:00:15,946 --> 01:00:18,155
Everybody, take out your paper.

1235
01:00:18,240 --> 01:00:22,785
And using the flashlight under your seat,
start to warm up that paper.

1236
01:00:22,953 --> 01:00:26,121
I think your correct balance begins to appear.

1237
01:00:29,834 --> 01:00:33,087
Now, Art, don't worry,
we have a flashlight for you.

1238
01:00:33,296 --> 01:00:34,338
Yes.

1239
01:00:35,257 --> 01:00:36,590
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

1240
01:00:37,842 --> 01:00:38,926
- Whoa!
- (HENLEY LAUGHS)

1241
01:00:41,096 --> 01:00:43,013
DANIEL: Look.
HENLEY: Huh? Wow.

1242
01:00:43,306 --> 01:00:44,515
What's going on there, Daniel?

1243
01:00:44,724 --> 01:00:50,145
Wait. This is weird.
A second ago, it said $144,579,651.

1244
01:00:50,230 --> 01:00:51,230
But now...

1245
01:00:51,856 --> 01:00:54,858
Now it says $70,000 less.

1246
01:00:58,238 --> 01:01:00,573
- Josepha, can you stand up?
- Yes.

1247
01:01:00,657 --> 01:01:02,283
Now, what is your new number?

1248
01:01:02,993 --> 01:01:07,329
$70,562 now in my account.

1249
01:01:07,497 --> 01:01:08,872
(CHEERING)

1250
01:01:10,625 --> 01:01:16,171
Is it possible that Josepha's balance went up
the exact amount that Art's went down?

1251
01:01:16,506 --> 01:01:19,008
Hey. Check it out. It's happening again.

1252
01:01:19,175 --> 01:01:20,217
DANIEL: Is it?

1253
01:01:21,511 --> 01:01:23,846
HENLEY: Wow. It is.

1254
01:01:24,180 --> 01:01:27,349
Art's balance has gone down another 280K.

1255
01:01:27,517 --> 01:01:29,560
Dina Robertson? What did yours say?

1256
01:01:29,811 --> 01:01:33,564
$281,477.

1257
01:01:33,982 --> 01:01:35,232
(CHEERING)

1258
01:01:37,527 --> 01:01:39,194
We have a confession to make.

1259
01:01:39,404 --> 01:01:41,405
She's right. We lied about something.

1260
01:01:41,489 --> 01:01:43,157
Yes. None of you were chosen at random.

1261
01:01:43,283 --> 01:01:45,701
All of you have one thing in common.

1262
01:01:46,244 --> 01:01:48,162
Everyone in this room was a victim

1263
01:01:48,246 --> 01:01:51,040
of the hard times that hit one of
America's most treasured cities.

1264
01:01:51,124 --> 01:01:53,709
Some of you lost your houses, your cars.

1265
01:01:54,210 --> 01:01:56,253
- Your businesses.
- Your loved ones.

1266
01:01:56,379 --> 01:01:59,548
But all of you were insured
by the same company.

1267
01:01:59,716 --> 01:02:01,342
ALL: Tressler Insurance.

1268
01:02:02,886 --> 01:02:03,886
MERRITT: You were abandoned.

1269
01:02:03,970 --> 01:02:05,054
You were loopholed...

1270
01:02:05,138 --> 01:02:06,347
...out of your settlements.

1271
01:02:07,724 --> 01:02:10,351
This is all for show. Correct?

1272
01:02:10,560 --> 01:02:11,810
"All" meaning we're doing it onstage

1273
01:02:11,895 --> 01:02:13,103
in front of a paying audience?

1274
01:02:13,271 --> 01:02:14,897
- Then, yes, it's for show.
- MAN: Whoa! Whoa!

1275
01:02:15,190 --> 01:02:17,691
I've got $82,000 in my bank account!

1276
01:02:17,859 --> 01:02:19,693
It says it right here on my cell phone!

1277
01:02:19,944 --> 01:02:22,905
Everybody, look at your cell phones
right now! Everybody!

1278
01:02:23,073 --> 01:02:24,073
(CELL PHONES CHIMING)

1279
01:02:24,783 --> 01:02:26,200
(ALL CHEERING)

1280
01:02:29,496 --> 01:02:30,579
Whoo!

1281
01:02:30,872 --> 01:02:31,872
Is this for real?

1282
01:02:32,082 --> 01:02:33,248
I don't know.

1283
01:02:33,541 --> 01:02:34,625
<i>DYLAN: Is this happening?</i>

1284
01:02:34,793 --> 01:02:36,377
I don't know! I can't tell!

1285
01:02:37,128 --> 01:02:39,254
Hey! Did you do this?

1286
01:02:40,465 --> 01:02:41,715
JACK: How could we, Art?

1287
01:02:41,925 --> 01:02:43,092
We don't have your password.

1288
01:02:43,259 --> 01:02:46,553
We'd need access to information
we could never get our hands on.

1289
01:02:46,763 --> 01:02:50,474
Ah, yes, security questions, for instance, like,
I don't know, your mother's maiden name

1290
01:02:50,600 --> 01:02:52,142
or the name of your first pet.

1291
01:02:52,268 --> 01:02:54,061
Where would we get that information, Art?

1292
01:02:54,437 --> 01:02:56,063
You certainly would never tell us.

1293
01:02:58,858 --> 01:03:01,068
<i>FULLER: We got confirmation.</i>
It's really happening. They robbed him.

1294
01:03:03,279 --> 01:03:04,738
Do not let them get away.

1295
01:03:04,823 --> 01:03:06,824
Hey, we left you the jet and the Rolls.

1296
01:03:12,080 --> 01:03:13,414
(SHOUTING ANGRILY)

1297
01:03:13,790 --> 01:03:15,124
You got hell to pay!

1298
01:03:18,128 --> 01:03:19,128
DYLAN: Stop!

1299
01:03:19,838 --> 01:03:21,630
Stop! Nobody move!

1300
01:03:23,591 --> 01:03:24,675
Freeze!

1301
01:03:24,926 --> 01:03:26,468
Quarterback!

1302
01:03:29,347 --> 01:03:31,765
ALL: We are The Four Horsemen.

1303
01:03:31,850 --> 01:03:32,891
Good night.

1304
01:03:32,976 --> 01:03:34,101
(GRUNTING)

1305
01:03:45,155 --> 01:03:46,530
DYLAN: Get 'em off me!

1306
01:03:47,282 --> 01:03:48,866
Get off! Get off me!

1307
01:03:56,708 --> 01:03:57,708
(SIRENS WAILING)

1308
01:03:59,252 --> 01:04:00,669
Get off me!

1309
01:04:08,970 --> 01:04:11,138
All right. I want everyone
on the street! Everyone!

1310
01:04:16,269 --> 01:04:17,352
(THADDEUS CHUCKLING)

1311
01:04:18,062 --> 01:04:19,897
ALL: Quarterback!

1312
01:04:21,441 --> 01:04:24,193
Fuller, meet me in front of the theater
and bring the tracker.

1313
01:04:24,736 --> 01:04:27,029
Let's go! Let's go! Now! Come on! Let's go!

1314
01:04:27,197 --> 01:04:28,280
Give me the tracker.

1315
01:04:28,740 --> 01:04:29,740
Let's go.

1316
01:04:33,953 --> 01:04:35,078
FBI! Clear!

1317
01:04:35,789 --> 01:04:36,789
- Dylan!
- DYLAN: Damn.

1318
01:04:37,081 --> 01:04:38,040
What have you got?

1319
01:04:38,124 --> 01:04:39,708
That's him right there. Follow the red dot.

1320
01:04:39,793 --> 01:04:42,836
All right, I'll take this.
Go. Box 'em. Cut 'em off that way.

1321
01:04:44,756 --> 01:04:46,256
He's turning left on Burgundy.

1322
01:05:00,939 --> 01:05:02,397
(CAR ALARMS BLARING)

1323
01:05:08,238 --> 01:05:09,238
(GRUNTS)

1324
01:05:09,906 --> 01:05:11,448
- DYLAN: Oh!
- (CRASHING)

1325
01:05:16,329 --> 01:05:17,788
(TRACKER BEEPING)

1326
01:05:23,336 --> 01:05:24,628
Hey! Move!

1327
01:05:24,963 --> 01:05:26,296
- Move! Move!
- Oh!

1328
01:05:26,589 --> 01:05:28,173
(ALL CLAMORING)

1329
01:05:28,925 --> 01:05:30,467
I got him heading north on Bourbon.

1330
01:05:30,844 --> 01:05:32,553
- Sorry. Move, move!
- Hey!

1331
01:05:32,637 --> 01:05:34,429
Hey, excuse me. Move, move! Excuse me.

1332
01:05:36,140 --> 01:05:37,182
Ow!

1333
01:05:45,900 --> 01:05:47,568
I've lost him at Bourbon.

1334
01:05:52,949 --> 01:05:54,324
Damn! Where are you?

1335
01:06:06,838 --> 01:06:08,046
Excuse me.

1336
01:06:14,345 --> 01:06:15,971
He's heading south on Exchange Place.

1337
01:06:18,516 --> 01:06:19,558
Stop!

1338
01:06:26,566 --> 01:06:27,774
What are you doing?

1339
01:06:31,362 --> 01:06:32,779
DYLAN: He's going in Napoleon House.

1340
01:06:32,864 --> 01:06:33,989
(SIREN WAILS)

1341
01:06:35,617 --> 01:06:37,576
- Move! Move!
- (WOMAN SCREAMS)

1342
01:06:38,036 --> 01:06:39,578
Move out of the way!

1343
01:06:40,246 --> 01:06:41,246
Hey!

1344
01:06:42,081 --> 01:06:43,081
Move!

1345
01:06:45,376 --> 01:06:47,628
He's in the bathroom.
I have him in the bathroom.

1346
01:06:47,754 --> 01:06:50,047
(GRUNTS) No! No! No!

1347
01:06:51,925 --> 01:06:53,091
AGENTS: Freeze!

1348
01:06:53,927 --> 01:06:55,385
- FULLER: Lower your weapons!
- (DEVICES BEEPING)

1349
01:06:55,470 --> 01:06:58,805
What? I'm tracking myself!

1350
01:06:59,307 --> 01:07:01,266
<i>NEWSCASTER: The Horsemen</i>
left egg on the face of what they call

1351
01:07:01,351 --> 01:07:06,647
<i>the alphabet agencies, calling into question</i>
the efficacy of the FBI's task force

1352
01:07:06,898 --> 01:07:09,399
<i>as well as the man in charge</i>
of the investigation,

1353
01:07:09,484 --> 01:07:12,986
<i>Special Agent Dylan Rhodes,</i>
who was publicly ridiculed,

1354
01:07:13,071 --> 01:07:15,948
<i>and even tackled at tonight's performance.</i>

1355
01:07:16,282 --> 01:07:17,574
<i>Talk about a fumble.</i>

1356
01:07:17,784 --> 01:07:19,618
<i>This is quickly becoming a national story,</i>

1357
01:07:19,702 --> 01:07:22,496
<i>as The Horsemen have now seemingly</i>
pulled off the impossible

1358
01:07:22,580 --> 01:07:24,873
<i>for the second time in as many days.</i>

1359
01:07:25,291 --> 01:07:28,460
<i>Two nights ago in Vegas, The Horsemen</i>
seemingly robbed a bank in Paris...

1360
01:07:28,628 --> 01:07:29,795
Hey.

1361
01:07:31,089 --> 01:07:33,632
- What are you doing?
- I'm having a drink.

1362
01:07:36,803 --> 01:07:38,136
I came to get you.

1363
01:07:38,596 --> 01:07:39,596
I'm worried about you.

1364
01:07:39,681 --> 01:07:41,515
You're worried about me.
Well, I'm worried about you.

1365
01:07:41,599 --> 01:07:44,059
- Atlas. You had him.
- He didn't have a weapon.

1366
01:07:44,143 --> 01:07:45,435
I couldn't shoot him and you know that.

1367
01:07:45,520 --> 01:07:48,355
Yeah, but you... You let him go.

1368
01:07:48,773 --> 01:07:49,982
Didn't you?

1369
01:07:50,775 --> 01:07:53,568
A pretty French girl shows up out of the blue,
acts like she's my partner

1370
01:07:53,653 --> 01:07:55,362
- and then she lets the bad guy go?
- Let go of my arm.

1371
01:07:55,446 --> 01:07:57,114
Who exactly are you anyway?

1372
01:07:58,116 --> 01:07:59,199
(GRUNTS)

1373
01:07:59,367 --> 01:08:01,368
I thought you said you were a desk agent.

1374
01:08:06,207 --> 01:08:07,457
Not bad.

1375
01:08:09,460 --> 01:08:10,460
What is this?

1376
01:08:13,506 --> 01:08:14,965
What's the Eye of Horus?

1377
01:08:15,174 --> 01:08:18,260
Oh, certainly nothing
I want to get into tonight.

1378
01:08:18,344 --> 01:08:20,887
You're dismissive enough
about me when you're sober.

1379
01:08:21,180 --> 01:08:23,056
Find your way back yourself.

1380
01:08:27,353 --> 01:08:30,564
Mr. Bradley? Mr. Tressler would like you
to join him for a drink.

1381
01:08:39,949 --> 01:08:40,991
Sir.

1382
01:08:41,200 --> 01:08:42,242
TRESSLER: Thank you.

1383
01:08:43,828 --> 01:08:46,038
What is your role with them?

1384
01:08:46,205 --> 01:08:47,205
Role?

1385
01:08:47,415 --> 01:08:49,124
Yes. You seem to know
everything about them.

1386
01:08:49,208 --> 01:08:51,126
What they're gonna do.
Where they're gonna be.

1387
01:08:51,210 --> 01:08:54,421
If it makes you feel any better,
this wasn't about you.

1388
01:08:54,505 --> 01:08:57,966
Please tell me why this was not about me.

1389
01:08:58,509 --> 01:09:01,094
This is a magic trick, Mr. Tressler.

1390
01:09:01,345 --> 01:09:03,680
Played out on a global scale.

1391
01:09:04,057 --> 01:09:08,018
You, sir, are the abracadabra.

1392
01:09:08,561 --> 01:09:11,354
The distraction,
while they set up the real trick.

1393
01:09:11,564 --> 01:09:15,734
I was a $140-million distraction?

1394
01:09:16,569 --> 01:09:17,736
Yes.

1395
01:09:18,404 --> 01:09:22,574
And that very ego that got you involved
with them in the first place

1396
01:09:23,034 --> 01:09:24,576
is what keeps you from seeing that.

1397
01:09:24,702 --> 01:09:25,994
- You know...
- "I can destroy you."

1398
01:09:26,079 --> 01:09:27,746
Yes, I do know.

1399
01:09:27,955 --> 01:09:29,247
Well, you won't.

1400
01:09:29,791 --> 01:09:31,958
And you won't destroy them.

1401
01:09:32,418 --> 01:09:37,214
Whatever this grand trick is,
it was designed a long time ago.

1402
01:09:37,423 --> 01:09:41,968
And I believe that what's about to follow
is really going to amaze.

1403
01:09:42,804 --> 01:09:47,349
So I suggest you sit back
and enjoy your front row seat.

1404
01:09:47,809 --> 01:09:50,477
You paid quite a lot of good money for it.

1405
01:09:50,686 --> 01:09:52,729
Whatever you stand to make...

1406
01:09:54,857 --> 01:09:58,401
I'll double it, if you expose them now.

1407
01:09:58,611 --> 01:09:59,945
And destroy them.

1408
01:10:00,404 --> 01:10:02,405
I stand to make five million.

1409
01:10:03,116 --> 01:10:04,366
Am I flinching?

1410
01:10:06,494 --> 01:10:08,078
No, you're not.

1411
01:11:28,993 --> 01:11:30,118
Hey.

1412
01:11:31,495 --> 01:11:33,663
I'm sorry for your arm.

1413
01:11:33,748 --> 01:11:35,332
No. I'm sorry.

1414
01:11:35,416 --> 01:11:37,667
I was an asshole. I was drunk.

1415
01:11:39,670 --> 01:11:42,255
I'm at a loss.

1416
01:11:44,175 --> 01:11:49,596
You know, when Merritt said I hardly spent
any time away from the desk, he was right.

1417
01:11:49,680 --> 01:11:52,974
I'm a researcher. That's what I do best.

1418
01:11:54,060 --> 01:11:57,979
So what's this all about?

1419
01:11:58,689 --> 01:12:01,316
Supposedly, if you buy into it,

1420
01:12:01,400 --> 01:12:04,069
The Eye are the keepers of real magic

1421
01:12:04,153 --> 01:12:07,030
and the protectors of those who practice it.

1422
01:12:07,114 --> 01:12:09,074
"Candidates for initiations

1423
01:12:09,158 --> 01:12:12,285
"must follow a series of commands
with blind obedience."

1424
01:12:13,329 --> 01:12:16,539
- This isn't real.
- But there are some who think it is.

1425
01:12:16,958 --> 01:12:18,541
May I?

1426
01:12:20,336 --> 01:12:24,381
According to this,
they only take new people twice a century.

1427
01:12:24,715 --> 01:12:28,134
So what? The Horsemen are doing
these shows in order to get into this thing?

1428
01:12:28,219 --> 01:12:29,427
- I don't know.
- I don't know.

1429
01:12:29,512 --> 01:12:34,516
I mean, I guess these guys
could just rob banks to rob banks.

1430
01:12:34,600 --> 01:12:36,935
They don't have to put on a show for that.

1431
01:12:37,019 --> 01:12:38,520
It's probably just a myth.

1432
01:12:38,604 --> 01:12:42,607
But it doesn't make any sense,
and I don't think logic will solve this for us.

1433
01:12:42,692 --> 01:12:45,276
- You don't say?
- No.

1434
01:12:46,654 --> 01:12:51,282
I believe that some things are only discovered

1435
01:12:51,367 --> 01:12:55,745
if you take certain leaps.

1436
01:13:02,753 --> 01:13:04,254
Well, I gotta get to...

1437
01:13:04,422 --> 01:13:05,880
Yeah. Yeah.

1438
01:13:05,965 --> 01:13:08,133
- Thanks. Good night.
- Yeah. Good night.

1439
01:13:08,217 --> 01:13:10,010
- Sorry.
- It's all right.

1440
01:13:12,513 --> 01:13:14,848
If The Eye did exist, we'd have to assume
they were watching us, right?

1441
01:13:14,932 --> 01:13:15,932
(PHONE BEEPING)

1442
01:13:16,100 --> 01:13:17,308
Shit.

1443
01:13:17,393 --> 01:13:20,020
I think someone is watching us,
but it isn't magic.

1444
01:13:20,104 --> 01:13:23,064
Your fears are correct.
This is not and has never been your phone.

1445
01:13:23,149 --> 01:13:27,861
It's a clone in every way, except for this.

1446
01:13:27,945 --> 01:13:29,237
A bug.

1447
01:13:29,321 --> 01:13:33,158
Someone has heard every call, read every text.

1448
01:13:33,325 --> 01:13:34,576
That's how they were able to stay ahead of us.

1449
01:13:34,660 --> 01:13:35,452
God damn it!

1450
01:13:36,954 --> 01:13:38,705
Get me Atlas' interrogation tape.

1451
01:13:38,956 --> 01:13:41,207
Yes, sir. I have it on the hard drive.

1452
01:13:42,334 --> 01:13:43,418
Picture's up.

1453
01:13:43,878 --> 01:13:45,628
DYLAN: Okay, fast forward.

1454
01:13:46,005 --> 01:13:47,464
Go on, go on. Freeze!

1455
01:13:48,257 --> 01:13:50,050
Okay. Frame by frame. Go on.

1456
01:13:50,926 --> 01:13:51,968
Play it through.

1457
01:13:53,095 --> 01:13:55,388
Ah! Stop. Zoom in tighter. Tighter.

1458
01:13:55,848 --> 01:13:57,640
There. That's where he took my phone.

1459
01:13:58,934 --> 01:14:00,226
Is that thing transmitting?

1460
01:14:00,311 --> 01:14:01,728
Only when you're making a call
or sending a text.

1461
01:14:01,896 --> 01:14:02,854
Plus I removed the bug.

1462
01:14:02,938 --> 01:14:04,481
All right. Put it back in and turn on the phone.

1463
01:14:04,732 --> 01:14:06,524
They don't know that we know about the bug.

1464
01:14:06,734 --> 01:14:08,735
As of this instant, we are ahead of them.

1465
01:14:08,819 --> 01:14:10,904
We need to keep it that way. Understand?

1466
01:14:11,363 --> 01:14:12,655
Find my real phone and track it.

1467
01:14:12,740 --> 01:14:15,784
Already did. As of about 20 minutes ago,
it's in New York City.

1468
01:14:16,327 --> 01:14:17,368
Good.

1469
01:14:17,745 --> 01:14:20,538
I wanna cut 'em off at the knees.
They got power? Cut it.

1470
01:14:20,831 --> 01:14:24,125
They got phones, electricity, water? Cut it.

1471
01:14:24,335 --> 01:14:27,087
Squeeze 'em out.
I want 'em to feel our presence.

1472
01:14:27,296 --> 01:14:28,755
And get me an airplane!

1473
01:14:31,550 --> 01:14:32,634
The firewall's down.

1474
01:14:32,718 --> 01:14:34,177
- Do they know about this?
- DANIEL: They who?

1475
01:14:34,261 --> 01:14:36,179
"They," "them," whoever we're working for.

1476
01:14:36,263 --> 01:14:39,891
Who are we working for?
And are we prepared to go to jail for them?

1477
01:14:39,975 --> 01:14:42,185
- DANIEL: Stop being paranoid.
- It really does happen.

1478
01:14:42,269 --> 01:14:44,104
It happened to you.
Doesn't mean it's gonna happen to us.

1479
01:14:44,188 --> 01:14:45,772
Guys, I don't know if can do this, all right.

1480
01:14:45,856 --> 01:14:47,148
I don't want to go to jail, you know?

1481
01:14:47,233 --> 01:14:49,025
Then don't screw up.
You're always talking about wanting

1482
01:14:49,110 --> 01:14:50,110
to be treated like an adult.

1483
01:14:50,194 --> 01:14:51,569
Now might be a good time
to start acting like one.

1484
01:14:51,654 --> 01:14:53,780
Stick to the plan. Stay here and burn it all.

1485
01:14:56,992 --> 01:14:58,243
(TIRES SCREECHING)

1486
01:15:06,919 --> 01:15:08,044
MERRITT: I don't know what I'm doing here.

1487
01:15:08,129 --> 01:15:09,212
I don't know what you would do
anywhere else.

1488
01:15:09,296 --> 01:15:12,090
I'm here for the pot of gold
at the end of the rainbow.

1489
01:15:12,174 --> 01:15:14,217
That's it. Then I'm gone.

1490
01:15:14,301 --> 01:15:16,678
You can do whatever you want
when this is over, Merritt.

1491
01:15:16,762 --> 01:15:18,721
But until then, you stick to the plan.

1492
01:15:18,806 --> 01:15:20,932
Hey, guys. Uh... They're here.

1493
01:15:22,852 --> 01:15:24,727
- My guys are ready to go.
- Let's do this quickly...

1494
01:15:24,937 --> 01:15:26,146
- Uh. No.
- What?

1495
01:15:26,230 --> 01:15:27,689
She doesn't have jurisdiction here.

1496
01:15:27,773 --> 01:15:28,982
She's Interpol. She's with me.

1497
01:15:29,066 --> 01:15:31,276
- She stays.
- What? What?

1498
01:15:31,569 --> 01:15:32,569
Stay in the car.

1499
01:15:34,822 --> 01:15:36,030
Let's go.

1500
01:15:41,829 --> 01:15:42,871
MERRITT: Okay. Let's do it.

1501
01:15:47,168 --> 01:15:48,168
FBI!

1502
01:15:52,423 --> 01:15:53,756
MERRITT: Ladies first.

1503
01:15:54,341 --> 01:15:55,633
- Don't move!
- (SCREAMING)

1504
01:16:01,140 --> 01:16:03,057
- (CELL PHONE RINGING)
- Tell me.

1505
01:16:03,142 --> 01:16:04,726
Is my money being well-spent?

1506
01:16:05,394 --> 01:16:07,270
- Exceedingly well.
- (CAMERA CLICKING)

1507
01:16:09,064 --> 01:16:10,565
Now you tell me,

1508
01:16:11,358 --> 01:16:12,692
how do you like your Horsemen?

1509
01:16:12,776 --> 01:16:15,153
Fricasseed or fried?

1510
01:16:15,237 --> 01:16:16,279
Shredded.

1511
01:16:17,615 --> 01:16:19,073
I'll tell the chef.

1512
01:17:24,682 --> 01:17:26,057
(GRUNTING)

1513
01:17:28,852 --> 01:17:30,186
(DISPOSAL WHIRRING)

1514
01:17:34,650 --> 01:17:35,650
Freeze!

1515
01:17:42,866 --> 01:17:43,992
- Dylan!
- (WHIRRING)

1516
01:17:44,785 --> 01:17:45,952
DYLAN: Hold on!

1517
01:17:48,289 --> 01:17:49,330
Oh, you little...

1518
01:17:53,836 --> 01:17:54,836
Come here!

1519
01:17:56,588 --> 01:17:58,506
OFFICER: Five is clear. Standing by for six.

1520
01:17:58,841 --> 01:18:00,717
- You little shit!
- (IMITATING) You little shit!

1521
01:18:00,968 --> 01:18:03,094
- What game are you playing?
- What game are you playing?

1522
01:18:03,595 --> 01:18:05,513
We're all good at six. Move to seven.

1523
01:18:05,597 --> 01:18:07,640
Copy that. Going to seven. Go, go, go!

1524
01:18:08,559 --> 01:18:10,226
No, no, no, no, no. Go back!

1525
01:18:11,103 --> 01:18:12,228
Hey!

1526
01:18:13,981 --> 01:18:15,231
DYLAN: Come here!

1527
01:18:18,610 --> 01:18:19,777
(GRUNTING)

1528
01:18:22,448 --> 01:18:23,656
Ah!

1529
01:18:46,263 --> 01:18:47,388
Come here!

1530
01:18:47,473 --> 01:18:49,182
All right, whoa, hold on, hold on!

1531
01:18:51,101 --> 01:18:52,935
- Really?
- Yup.

1532
01:18:53,437 --> 01:18:54,437
Ow!

1533
01:18:57,107 --> 01:18:58,107
Oh, you...

1534
01:18:59,485 --> 01:19:00,485
Ow!

1535
01:19:01,528 --> 01:19:02,987
You little... (YELLING)

1536
01:19:09,203 --> 01:19:10,203
(GRUNTS)

1537
01:19:19,421 --> 01:19:20,463
Shit!

1538
01:19:27,179 --> 01:19:28,304
(DYLAN YELLING)

1539
01:19:38,857 --> 01:19:39,899
Shit!

1540
01:19:39,983 --> 01:19:41,150
(PANTING)

1541
01:19:41,318 --> 01:19:42,318
Give me that!

1542
01:19:42,569 --> 01:19:43,611
(GROANS)

1543
01:20:06,385 --> 01:20:07,635
(CAR LOCK CHIRPS)

1544
01:20:08,554 --> 01:20:10,138
<i>FULLER: All units, cover the north exit now!</i>

1545
01:20:10,222 --> 01:20:11,305
Clear on Evan.

1546
01:20:11,849 --> 01:20:13,391
<i>FULLER: Block every possible exit.</i>

1547
01:20:13,517 --> 01:20:14,642
Hey! Get back... Shit.

1548
01:20:16,395 --> 01:20:18,521
- FBI. Sort of. I need your car. Thanks.
- What?

1549
01:20:18,605 --> 01:20:19,605
What?

1550
01:20:22,234 --> 01:20:23,860
Stop! Stop!

1551
01:20:32,202 --> 01:20:33,286
(GRUNTS)

1552
01:20:40,002 --> 01:20:41,043
Hey!

1553
01:20:43,380 --> 01:20:45,798
- (GROANING)
- (HANDCUFFS CLICKING)

1554
01:21:10,824 --> 01:21:11,824
Good. Follow him!

1555
01:21:11,909 --> 01:21:13,993
Don't ever tell me to stay in the car. Ever.

1556
01:21:14,077 --> 01:21:15,411
I didn't have tactical command.

1557
01:21:15,495 --> 01:21:17,830
If you don't trust me, just tell me.

1558
01:21:17,915 --> 01:21:19,498
Promise me, next time, you will back me up.

1559
01:21:19,583 --> 01:21:21,667
Could we have
this conversation later, please?

1560
01:21:21,752 --> 01:21:23,336
No!

1561
01:21:23,420 --> 01:21:25,630
Okay, fine, I promise. Now, go!

1562
01:21:27,925 --> 01:21:29,342
(TIRES SQUEALING)

1563
01:21:33,055 --> 01:21:35,598
- Whoa! Where'd they go?
- Where are they?

1564
01:21:35,849 --> 01:21:37,516
I don't know. She just took some guy's car.

1565
01:21:37,601 --> 01:21:39,060
- Where are they?
- That way. That way.

1566
01:21:39,144 --> 01:21:40,186
- Is that your car?
- Yeah.

1567
01:21:40,270 --> 01:21:41,729
Let's go.

1568
01:21:55,827 --> 01:21:56,953
(GRUNTS)

1569
01:21:57,120 --> 01:21:58,120
- (BRAKES SQUEAL)
- Whoa!

1570
01:22:07,256 --> 01:22:08,297
There he is!

1571
01:22:17,766 --> 01:22:19,308
(SIRENS WAILING)

1572
01:22:20,102 --> 01:22:21,102
DYLAN: Move!

1573
01:22:25,482 --> 01:22:26,524
Left!

1574
01:22:28,819 --> 01:22:30,361
We're heading east on the FDR Drive.

1575
01:22:30,570 --> 01:22:32,488
- This is not east.
- North! North!

1576
01:22:32,572 --> 01:22:34,615
- We're heading north on the FDR Drive.
- What?

1577
01:22:34,700 --> 01:22:36,784
<i>MALE NEWSCASTER: We're coming</i>
to you live above the FDR,

1578
01:22:36,868 --> 01:22:39,787
<i>where NYPD and federal agents,</i>
as you now see,

1579
01:22:39,871 --> 01:22:43,207
<i>are engaged in a high-speed pursuit,</i>
following a black sedan.

1580
01:22:48,338 --> 01:22:49,338
<i>DYLAN: Fuller, where are you?</i>

1581
01:22:49,840 --> 01:22:51,507
Right here. Trying to catch up to you now.

1582
01:22:51,675 --> 01:22:53,718
<i>NEWSCASTER: We're now trying</i>
to get you a better shot.

1583
01:22:56,221 --> 01:22:57,346
Come on!

1584
01:23:04,604 --> 01:23:05,646
Whoa!

1585
01:23:05,731 --> 01:23:06,731
Sorry.

1586
01:23:09,901 --> 01:23:10,901
Whoa!

1587
01:23:12,946 --> 01:23:16,157
<i>NEWSCASTER: It looks like they're turning</i>
onto the 59th Street Bridge.

1588
01:23:18,327 --> 01:23:22,330
<i>As soon as we have them within range,</i>
we will bring you those pictures live.

1589
01:23:27,377 --> 01:23:28,544
Good. Just stay with him.

1590
01:23:31,298 --> 01:23:32,631
(SIRENS WAILING)

1591
01:23:35,927 --> 01:23:37,178
Go, go, go!

1592
01:23:38,013 --> 01:23:39,055
(YELLS)

1593
01:23:41,224 --> 01:23:42,725
Behind... You're behind the bus!

1594
01:23:46,313 --> 01:23:47,396
Get over!

1595
01:23:48,148 --> 01:23:49,231
Ha-ha!

1596
01:23:50,942 --> 01:23:51,984
Oh, shit!

1597
01:23:54,446 --> 01:23:55,488
Uh-oh!

1598
01:24:15,550 --> 01:24:16,550
Come here!

1599
01:24:17,844 --> 01:24:19,261
Get back! Get back!

1600
01:24:20,722 --> 01:24:22,056
Dylan, let's go, man!

1601
01:24:22,224 --> 01:24:23,265
Come on, you...

1602
01:24:24,726 --> 01:24:26,811
FULLER: Come on, man! Get out!
DYLAN: He's gonna die in here.

1603
01:24:26,895 --> 01:24:30,231
Leave him! There's nothing you can do!
Let's go! Leave him!

1604
01:24:35,070 --> 01:24:36,445
- DYLAN: The paper!
- FULLER: Dylan!

1605
01:24:36,696 --> 01:24:38,614
Let's go! Let's go! Come on!

1606
01:25:03,932 --> 01:25:05,975
<i>NEWSCASTER: Today,</i>
the unfolding story of a popular

1607
01:25:06,143 --> 01:25:08,185
<i>and controversial group of magicians,</i>

1608
01:25:08,270 --> 01:25:10,271
<i>who have been fast capturing</i>
the public's imagination,

1609
01:25:10,355 --> 01:25:13,691
<i>took a dark turn</i>
when a police action that began in Chinatown

1610
01:25:13,775 --> 01:25:17,570
<i>developed into a dramatic, high-speed chase</i>
across the 59th Street Bridge,

1611
01:25:17,654 --> 01:25:20,614
<i>which caused a fatal collision</i>
that took the life of Jack Wilder,

1612
01:25:20,699 --> 01:25:22,992
<i>one of the so-called Four Horsemen.</i>

1613
01:25:24,202 --> 01:25:28,289
<i>The whereabouts of the other three</i>
Horsemen remain unknown at this time.

1614
01:25:33,170 --> 01:25:35,713
FULLER: Dylan, they just
figured out what the paper was in Jack's car.

1615
01:25:35,839 --> 01:25:37,006
So they know what it is?

1616
01:25:37,215 --> 01:25:38,841
And why the kid died trying to protect it.

1617
01:25:39,009 --> 01:25:40,551
Evans is on his way to brief us right now.

1618
01:25:40,760 --> 01:25:41,802
Let's go.

1619
01:25:42,387 --> 01:25:43,721
You're gonna wanna take this first, though.

1620
01:25:43,805 --> 01:25:44,763
What's that?

1621
01:25:44,848 --> 01:25:46,557
Your friend Thaddeus Bradley.

1622
01:25:47,684 --> 01:25:48,684
Rhodes.

1623
01:25:49,019 --> 01:25:50,603
You do understand the function

1624
01:25:50,687 --> 01:25:52,855
of the magician's assistant,
don't you, Agent Rhodes?

1625
01:25:53,190 --> 01:25:55,858
Yeah, she's there to distract them
while he sets up the trick.

1626
01:25:56,276 --> 01:25:59,278
(CHUCKLES) You'd be right
if you weren't so wrong.

1627
01:25:59,696 --> 01:26:01,405
<i>While you're watching the magician,</i>

1628
01:26:02,073 --> 01:26:04,658
<i>that lovely innocent is actually</i>
pulling the strings.

1629
01:26:04,743 --> 01:26:07,828
<i>Don't you find it peculiar that Interpol</i>
would send you

1630
01:26:07,913 --> 01:26:11,415
a first timer off the desk to be your assistant?

1631
01:26:11,917 --> 01:26:14,084
Why did she request to be put on the case?

1632
01:26:14,419 --> 01:26:16,378
<i>- She was assigned to the case.</i>
- Oh.

1633
01:26:17,380 --> 01:26:18,756
Luck of the draw.

1634
01:26:19,216 --> 01:26:22,259
Like choosing a random card in the deck.

1635
01:26:22,469 --> 01:26:26,013
I find it odd, your sudden act of generosity.

1636
01:26:26,097 --> 01:26:27,264
What's in it for you?

1637
01:26:27,432 --> 01:26:29,266
Just trying to even the game.

1638
01:26:29,559 --> 01:26:33,395
I feel like I'm playing with somebody
wearing ankle weights and flippers.

1639
01:26:34,606 --> 01:26:38,400
Keep up, Agent Rhodes. Keep up.

1640
01:26:42,239 --> 01:26:43,280
FULLER: Hey.

1641
01:26:43,615 --> 01:26:44,823
We got a problem.

1642
01:26:45,992 --> 01:26:47,076
COWAN: Here's the safe.

1643
01:26:47,160 --> 01:26:49,954
No, no, no. Hey. What's he doing here?

1644
01:26:50,121 --> 01:26:51,580
Giving us our first solid lead.

1645
01:26:51,665 --> 01:26:54,750
We've been investigating a private security
contractor called Elkhorn

1646
01:26:54,834 --> 01:26:56,502
- for the last five years.
- And?

1647
01:26:56,586 --> 01:26:58,712
They've been hiding close
to a half billion dollars...

1648
01:26:58,797 --> 01:27:01,298
I didn't ask you. I asked him.

1649
01:27:01,675 --> 01:27:03,884
The money's in a vault inside
a warehouse in Queens.

1650
01:27:03,969 --> 01:27:06,470
We think this vault
is your magicians' final target.

1651
01:27:06,846 --> 01:27:08,555
COWAN: The magician
who died on the bridge...

1652
01:27:08,640 --> 01:27:12,268
You pulled our classified Elkhorn file
right from his crispy little hand.

1653
01:27:12,560 --> 01:27:14,895
And despite their bullshit
Robin Hood razzle-dazzle,

1654
01:27:14,980 --> 01:27:16,730
your magicians are nothing
more than common thieves.

1655
01:27:16,815 --> 01:27:17,982
How did they get the file?

1656
01:27:19,442 --> 01:27:22,444
This is the part you're gonna find
particularly interesting, Agent Rhodes.

1657
01:27:22,654 --> 01:27:27,366
They patched to my server after they accessed
your mobile command center in New Orleans

1658
01:27:27,450 --> 01:27:29,034
with codes they got from your phone.

1659
01:27:31,162 --> 01:27:32,997
You ordered us all out to chase after them.

1660
01:27:33,456 --> 01:27:35,916
The level of incompetence
displayed on this case,

1661
01:27:36,001 --> 01:27:38,002
that's a magic trick in and of itself.

1662
01:27:38,670 --> 01:27:40,963
Abracadabra. I'm taking over.

1663
01:27:42,382 --> 01:27:44,300
Boss, he's taking over?

1664
01:27:44,843 --> 01:27:46,343
EVANS: Let's go, gentlemen.

1665
01:27:48,179 --> 01:27:49,179
DYLAN: Hey.

1666
01:27:49,306 --> 01:27:51,181
Hey. I want to have a word with you.

1667
01:27:51,266 --> 01:27:52,391
Don't ever talk to me like that again.

1668
01:27:52,475 --> 01:27:54,852
- Why the hell did you take this case?
- What?

1669
01:27:54,936 --> 01:27:57,021
People say I'm "hard to read."
That's an American expression.

1670
01:27:57,105 --> 01:27:58,355
Do you understand it?

1671
01:27:58,481 --> 01:27:59,523
Yes.

1672
01:27:59,649 --> 01:28:01,650
Good, then let me make myself
perfectly clear to you.

1673
01:28:01,860 --> 01:28:05,654
If I find out that you are anything other than
who you say you are, I swear...

1674
01:28:05,780 --> 01:28:07,489
And we French also have an expression.

1675
01:28:08,158 --> 01:28:09,283
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

1676
01:28:09,367 --> 01:28:10,951
"Faith can move mountains."

1677
01:28:11,161 --> 01:28:14,788
If we hope to capture The Horsemen,
then you need to have a little faith in me.

1678
01:28:14,998 --> 01:28:16,999
Because I've done nothing
to deserve otherwise.

1679
01:28:17,167 --> 01:28:19,793
I just got my ass handed to me.

1680
01:28:19,878 --> 01:28:21,420
I am losing this case.

1681
01:28:21,504 --> 01:28:24,840
So faith is a luxury
I don't have any time for right now.

1682
01:28:31,056 --> 01:28:33,265
<i>DANIEL: More than anything in his life,</i>

1683
01:28:33,350 --> 01:28:38,771
Jack wanted to be
the most famous magician who ever lived.

1684
01:28:38,855 --> 01:28:40,230
And I can't say he achieved it,

1685
01:28:40,315 --> 01:28:44,234
but I do hope wherever he is,
it is full of magic.

1686
01:28:46,029 --> 01:28:48,364
But the point is... Sorry.

1687
01:28:48,448 --> 01:28:49,907
The point is...

1688
01:28:49,991 --> 01:28:56,205
The point of why we are here is to say
that we are not... We cannot quit now.

1689
01:28:56,289 --> 01:28:58,791
<i>We've started something bigger than all of us.</i>

1690
01:28:58,875 --> 01:29:00,709
<i>We have to finish it.</i>

1691
01:29:03,254 --> 01:29:04,922
(SIRENS WAILING)

1692
01:29:09,803 --> 01:29:10,886
<i>MAN: Approaching the warehouse.</i>

1693
01:29:11,054 --> 01:29:13,597
<i>Units 5 and 6
cover the north and south entrances.

1694
01:29:13,848 --> 01:29:15,099
<i>We are going for the vault.</i>

1695
01:29:19,938 --> 01:29:22,856
Hey. Where's the safe? Where's the safe?

1696
01:29:27,070 --> 01:29:28,028
EVANS: What is this?

1697
01:29:28,113 --> 01:29:29,405
Where the hell is the goddamn safe?

1698
01:29:29,572 --> 01:29:31,365
We just moved it while you were outside.

1699
01:29:31,533 --> 01:29:32,699
- Evans' orders.
- COWAN: What?

1700
01:29:32,784 --> 01:29:33,826
I never said that.

1701
01:29:33,910 --> 01:29:36,870
Sir, you got a phone call
and said Washington wants the safe moved.

1702
01:29:37,080 --> 01:29:39,123
You never heard that
come out of my mouth, Agent.

1703
01:29:39,249 --> 01:29:39,748
What happened?

1704
01:29:39,916 --> 01:29:42,292
What happened? You tell me what's going on,
because this is bullshit!

1705
01:29:42,377 --> 01:29:43,752
No!

1706
01:29:45,672 --> 01:29:47,297
(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)

1707
01:29:49,634 --> 01:29:51,135
Jesus Christ.

1708
01:29:51,302 --> 01:29:54,304
Sir? Sir? What are you doing?

1709
01:29:54,389 --> 01:29:56,223
I think it's Beethoven's Concerto in D-Major.

1710
01:29:56,307 --> 01:29:58,475
- Where's the safe?
- His team is loading the truck.

1711
01:30:02,814 --> 01:30:04,481
- Hey! Hey!
- Hey!

1712
01:30:06,025 --> 01:30:07,192
- DYLAN: Stop the truck!
- Stop!

1713
01:30:08,194 --> 01:30:09,611
- Stop!
- Hey! Stop that truck!

1714
01:30:10,321 --> 01:30:12,364
(DYLAN AND FULLER CONTINUE YELLING)

1715
01:30:18,997 --> 01:30:20,873
What the hell's going on? We got our orders.

1716
01:30:20,957 --> 01:30:22,458
Now you've got new orders. Open it up.

1717
01:30:26,671 --> 01:30:28,130
Okay. Here's what I want.

1718
01:30:28,506 --> 01:30:30,799
At this moment,
they think that safe's leaving this site.

1719
01:30:31,176 --> 01:30:34,303
So we stay with it.
We follow it all the way to... Where's it going?

1720
01:30:34,387 --> 01:30:35,637
5 Pointz. Up the street.

1721
01:30:35,972 --> 01:30:38,849
So we go to 5 Pointz.
Wherever the safe goes, we go.

1722
01:30:39,017 --> 01:30:40,142
It'll lead us right to 'em.

1723
01:30:41,019 --> 01:30:42,227
You two are with me.

1724
01:30:54,991 --> 01:30:55,991
Guys...

1725
01:30:57,076 --> 01:30:59,495
Look. Office just called with this.

1726
01:30:59,579 --> 01:31:01,622
Horsemen posted it to YouTube
20 minutes ago.

1727
01:31:01,706 --> 01:31:05,667
<i>The point of why we're here</i>
is to say that we are not...

1728
01:31:05,752 --> 01:31:07,544
<i>We cannot quit now.</i>

1729
01:31:07,754 --> 01:31:11,715
<i>We've started something bigger than all of us.</i>
We have to finish it.

1730
01:31:11,799 --> 01:31:14,635
<i>Remember the name Jack Wilder</i>
when you see us live,

1731
01:31:14,719 --> 01:31:16,512
<i>5 Pointz, Queens, 7:00.</i>

1732
01:31:16,596 --> 01:31:19,139
Their show is in a half an hour.
It's exactly where we're headed.

1733
01:31:19,224 --> 01:31:21,642
I don't know, boss.
I don't wanna be the naysayer,

1734
01:31:21,726 --> 01:31:23,644
but these guys are kinda tricky.

1735
01:31:23,728 --> 01:31:26,355
Rhodes, they're entertainers.

1736
01:31:28,942 --> 01:31:31,109
<i>NEWSCASTER 1: A stunning</i>
turnout here in 5 Pointz

1737
01:31:31,194 --> 01:31:34,488
<i>as the renegade Horsemen</i>
taunt the FBI into a final showdown.

1738
01:31:34,572 --> 01:31:36,490
<i>NEWSCASTER 2: The Horsemen have</i>
invited us to their final round

1739
01:31:36,574 --> 01:31:38,742
<i>of their three-act face-off with the FBI.</i>

1740
01:31:39,244 --> 01:31:42,621
<i>What do they have in store?</i>
We're about to find out.

1741
01:31:42,747 --> 01:31:44,540
(CROWD CHEERING)

1742
01:31:45,291 --> 01:31:46,792
(SIRENS WAILING)

1743
01:31:53,967 --> 01:31:56,176
<i>COWAN: All eyes on the truck.</i>
Let's see who approaches.

1744
01:31:56,261 --> 01:31:57,261
Copy that.

1745
01:32:13,820 --> 01:32:15,612
FEMALE FBI AGENT: Agents Rhodes, Fuller?

1746
01:32:16,322 --> 01:32:17,322
Go, for us.

1747
01:32:17,448 --> 01:32:19,950
We've got movement.
Someone's walking toward the truck.

1748
01:32:20,159 --> 01:32:21,285
<i>It's a woman.</i>

1749
01:32:25,456 --> 01:32:26,832
- FULLER: Freeze!
- Oh, shit!

1750
01:32:26,916 --> 01:32:28,125
(GUNS COCKING)

1751
01:32:28,418 --> 01:32:29,918
THADDEUS: What the hell's going on?

1752
01:32:30,962 --> 01:32:33,297
COWAN: Hey! It's the guy from the TV.

1753
01:32:33,381 --> 01:32:34,423
Put your guns down.

1754
01:32:34,674 --> 01:32:37,384
Look who it is. The fifth Horseman.

1755
01:32:37,468 --> 01:32:40,679
Are you kidding?
I'm following them, just like you are.

1756
01:32:40,763 --> 01:32:43,932
I'm not following anybody anymore.
You've been ahead of us this whole time.

1757
01:32:44,017 --> 01:32:45,642
But guess what? I'm ahead of you now.

1758
01:32:45,977 --> 01:32:47,644
Your ass is mine.

1759
01:32:47,812 --> 01:32:49,479
You guys are still idiots.

1760
01:32:49,564 --> 01:32:51,815
- Yeah?
- This happens to be the former

1761
01:32:51,899 --> 01:32:53,984
rehearsal space for Lionel Shrike.

1762
01:32:54,652 --> 01:32:56,486
It's where I did my first show.

1763
01:32:56,654 --> 01:32:59,489
Now, if you wanna look
like even bigger idiots,

1764
01:32:59,657 --> 01:33:00,949
why not open it?

1765
01:33:01,326 --> 01:33:02,951
And while you're doing it, Agent Rhodes,

1766
01:33:03,369 --> 01:33:07,039
would you mind reenacting your look
of absolute befuddlement for me?

1767
01:33:07,290 --> 01:33:09,374
It will make a wonderful cover for my DVD.

1768
01:33:10,835 --> 01:33:11,835
Open the safe.

1769
01:33:11,919 --> 01:33:12,961
- Go ahead.
- DYLAN: Open it.

1770
01:33:16,966 --> 01:33:18,675
- (BEEPS)
- AGENT: What the hell?

1771
01:33:21,220 --> 01:33:22,304
What?

1772
01:33:22,555 --> 01:33:26,016
Give me that. No. No!

1773
01:33:29,312 --> 01:33:30,562
(LOCK TUMBLERS MOVING)

1774
01:33:30,688 --> 01:33:31,730
What is this?

1775
01:33:32,023 --> 01:33:33,732
- (CLUNKING)
- Get back!

1776
01:33:39,489 --> 01:33:40,864
(BALLOONS SQUEAKING)

1777
01:33:41,282 --> 01:33:43,408
Who doesn't love a good magic trick?

1778
01:33:44,202 --> 01:33:46,536
They have you chasing empty safes again.

1779
01:33:47,872 --> 01:33:51,083
Once again, misdirection.

1780
01:33:58,049 --> 01:33:59,549
The show is starting. Move out!

1781
01:33:59,759 --> 01:34:02,219
The question I'd be asking now,
Agent Rhodes is...

1782
01:34:02,720 --> 01:34:04,888
"What happened to the real one?"

1783
01:34:21,739 --> 01:34:22,948
(SIRENS BLARING)

1784
01:34:25,535 --> 01:34:27,285
COWAN: Clear! Clear 'em out!

1785
01:34:27,370 --> 01:34:28,912
Come on. Move 'em out.
Move 'em out of the way.

1786
01:34:30,373 --> 01:34:32,249
FBI! Give me a path!

1787
01:34:32,875 --> 01:34:34,459
Clear out! Clear out!

1788
01:34:34,711 --> 01:34:36,086
DANIEL: What is magic?

1789
01:34:36,921 --> 01:34:37,963
<i>Magic is deception.</i>

1790
01:34:38,089 --> 01:34:41,591
<i>But deception designed to delight,</i>
to entertain, to inspire.

1791
01:34:41,676 --> 01:34:44,136
Look out! Clear! Clear! Look out!

1792
01:34:44,595 --> 01:34:45,721
DANIEL: It is about belief.

1793
01:34:45,805 --> 01:34:46,805
MERRITT: Faith.

1794
01:34:46,931 --> 01:34:47,889
HENLEY: Trust.

1795
01:34:47,974 --> 01:34:49,099
(CROWD CHEERING)

1796
01:34:51,936 --> 01:34:53,270
<i>Without those qualities,</i>

1797
01:34:53,396 --> 01:34:56,815
<i>magic, as an art form, would no longer exist.</i>

1798
01:34:57,400 --> 01:35:01,528
<i>HENLEY: But what happens if these qualities</i>
are not used for their higher purpose?

1799
01:35:01,612 --> 01:35:04,281
<i>And instead they're used to cheat, lie.</i>

1800
01:35:04,365 --> 01:35:06,575
<i>DANIEL: For personal gain or for greed.</i>

1801
01:35:06,993 --> 01:35:08,744
<i>Then it's no longer magic.</i>

1802
01:35:08,828 --> 01:35:09,911
<i>It's crime.</i>

1803
01:35:10,121 --> 01:35:16,251
<i>So tonight, for our final act,</i>
you're gonna help us set a few things right.

1804
01:35:20,173 --> 01:35:21,339
What's going on here, Rhodes?

1805
01:35:21,591 --> 01:35:22,758
I don't know.

1806
01:35:23,801 --> 01:35:25,010
Showtime.

1807
01:35:30,141 --> 01:35:31,183
Look!

1808
01:35:35,480 --> 01:35:37,397
There they are on the roof. Let's move!

1809
01:35:37,482 --> 01:35:38,815
Go, go, go!

1810
01:35:39,525 --> 01:35:40,817
- Dylan!
- FBI, coming through!

1811
01:35:42,278 --> 01:35:43,236
What are you doing here?

1812
01:35:43,321 --> 01:35:45,864
They're going in the wrong direction
and you know it.

1813
01:35:46,199 --> 01:35:48,408
Rhodes! I need all personnel now!

1814
01:35:48,493 --> 01:35:51,828
You need to trust me. Take your leap of faith.

1815
01:35:52,789 --> 01:35:53,830
Wait.

1816
01:35:54,290 --> 01:35:55,415
I'm going to go with her.

1817
01:35:55,625 --> 01:35:56,833
Go. I got your back. I'll be right here.

1818
01:35:58,503 --> 01:35:59,377
Go ahead!

1819
01:35:59,545 --> 01:36:01,004
That's on you, Fuller.

1820
01:36:16,646 --> 01:36:20,649
Let's go, let's go! Now, now, now!

1821
01:36:31,827 --> 01:36:32,869
Daniel?

1822
01:36:33,621 --> 01:36:34,829
- Yeah?
- Uh...

1823
01:36:34,956 --> 01:36:39,417
As our, let's call it, year of living dangerously

1824
01:36:39,502 --> 01:36:43,046
comes to a close,
in a rare moment of vulnerability,

1825
01:36:43,130 --> 01:36:47,842
I'd like to express a sentiment
to you about our relationship.

1826
01:36:47,927 --> 01:36:48,969
Okay.

1827
01:36:49,303 --> 01:36:52,806
Well, when I first met you,
I thought you were kind of a

1828
01:36:54,642 --> 01:36:56,560
- dick.
- (LAUGHS) Oh.

1829
01:36:56,644 --> 01:36:58,019
(LAUGHS) And?

1830
01:37:00,022 --> 01:37:01,690
No, that's it.

1831
01:37:01,941 --> 01:37:02,899
That's very nice.

1832
01:37:02,984 --> 01:37:04,401
- Yeah.
- I'm touched.

1833
01:37:04,485 --> 01:37:06,069
Yeah. Just from the heart.

1834
01:37:06,320 --> 01:37:07,821
Well, I didn't tell you where I was touched.

1835
01:37:07,905 --> 01:37:08,947
Oh, you!

1836
01:37:09,031 --> 01:37:10,198
(CHUCKLING)

1837
01:37:12,660 --> 01:37:14,327
Oh, God.
What are we gonna do when this is over?

1838
01:37:14,620 --> 01:37:17,455
We're on our own.
Our instructions run out after the show.

1839
01:37:18,332 --> 01:37:21,793
Even if there is no "Eye,"
if we were completely played and we spend

1840
01:37:21,877 --> 01:37:26,381
the next 20 years in jail, then,
I just want to say that...

1841
01:37:26,632 --> 01:37:29,009
I know. Me, too.

1842
01:37:29,343 --> 01:37:32,304
Whoa. (LAUGHS)
Little too sentimental for me.

1843
01:37:37,143 --> 01:37:38,643
(CHEERING)

1844
01:37:39,228 --> 01:37:40,312
There they are!

1845
01:37:43,316 --> 01:37:46,026
Go grab 'em! Put 'em down! Go, go, go!

1846
01:37:46,193 --> 01:37:47,193
Grab 'em!

1847
01:37:48,696 --> 01:37:49,738
(CROWD GROANS)

1848
01:37:51,032 --> 01:37:52,073
(CROWD LAUGHING)

1849
01:37:52,199 --> 01:37:53,241
Get up!

1850
01:37:53,701 --> 01:37:54,868
What the hell?

1851
01:37:58,664 --> 01:37:59,831
Ah, shit!

1852
01:38:00,916 --> 01:38:02,417
(PANTING)

1853
01:38:09,050 --> 01:38:10,550
- HENLEY: Hello, New York!
- (CROWD CHEERING)

1854
01:38:18,768 --> 01:38:20,644
Thank you for the magic.

1855
01:38:20,895 --> 01:38:25,106
And thank you for being such
an incredible and dedicated audience.

1856
01:38:25,524 --> 01:38:29,402
Unfortunately, like all good things,
it must come to an end.

1857
01:38:32,114 --> 01:38:34,282
So we would like to start our show tonight...

1858
01:38:34,700 --> 01:38:36,242
By saying goodbye.

1859
01:38:36,410 --> 01:38:37,494
(CHEERING)

1860
01:38:37,578 --> 01:38:40,789
HENLEY: All we wanted was to
bring the world to a magic show.

1861
01:38:40,873 --> 01:38:43,416
DANIEL: And thereby bring a little magic
back to the world.

1862
01:38:47,797 --> 01:38:48,922
DYLAN: Clear the way!

1863
01:38:58,724 --> 01:39:01,935
MERRITT: This has been
one hell of a ride for all of us.

1864
01:39:02,436 --> 01:39:04,771
But it's time for us to disappear.

1865
01:39:04,980 --> 01:39:06,314
DANIEL: Good night, New York.

1866
01:39:06,565 --> 01:39:07,941
MERRITT: And thank you for believing in us.

1867
01:39:10,611 --> 01:39:11,778
DYLAN: Stop!

1868
01:39:15,282 --> 01:39:16,282
Freeze!

1869
01:39:17,118 --> 01:39:18,326
- No!
- (GUNSHOT)

1870
01:39:35,970 --> 01:39:37,262
God damn it!

1871
01:40:05,875 --> 01:40:07,083
I'm sorry.

1872
01:40:07,710 --> 01:40:09,836
You were right. It's bigger than all of us.

1873
01:40:10,838 --> 01:40:14,924
This is one time I'm not happy being right.

1874
01:40:17,219 --> 01:40:18,970
So I guess this is it.

1875
01:40:20,890 --> 01:40:22,056
Is it?

1876
01:40:48,042 --> 01:40:49,334
Dylan!

1877
01:40:49,752 --> 01:40:52,003
Dylan! Dylan!

1878
01:40:52,296 --> 01:40:53,338
Hey.

1879
01:40:54,757 --> 01:40:56,674
- You see that?
- What?

1880
01:41:00,346 --> 01:41:01,721
Where's the real money?

1881
01:41:08,312 --> 01:41:09,437
(CAR ALARM BLARING)

1882
01:41:17,947 --> 01:41:21,908
MAN: You're under arrest!
Hands in the air! Now!

1883
01:42:13,043 --> 01:42:14,168
I've been framed.

1884
01:42:15,504 --> 01:42:18,047
- I'm sure you were.
- Yeah, but I can prove it.

1885
01:42:18,382 --> 01:42:19,674
I always do.

1886
01:42:20,050 --> 01:42:22,010
Just like I predicted that you'd play the fool.

1887
01:42:22,094 --> 01:42:24,596
Let's just drop the theatricality, all right?

1888
01:42:24,847 --> 01:42:27,015
The cameras aren't rolling in here.

1889
01:42:27,224 --> 01:42:29,684
Fellas, can I have a few minutes
with my friend here alone, please.

1890
01:42:29,768 --> 01:42:30,894
GUARD: Sure.

1891
01:42:36,609 --> 01:42:37,650
THADDEUS: All right.

1892
01:42:38,694 --> 01:42:40,320
- I got information to trade.
- Mmm.

1893
01:42:40,404 --> 01:42:41,529
I believe that's how it's done. Huh?

1894
01:42:41,614 --> 01:42:43,239
If it's of some value.

1895
01:42:45,910 --> 01:42:49,078
These bars give a man time to think.

1896
01:42:50,247 --> 01:42:53,541
And I'm pretty sure I know how they did it.

1897
01:42:54,209 --> 01:42:56,294
<i>Remember the rabbit trick</i>
in the second show?

1898
01:42:57,254 --> 01:42:59,088
<i>The box was never empty.</i>

1899
01:43:00,174 --> 01:43:01,341
(WHIRRING)

1900
01:43:01,467 --> 01:43:02,634
<i>The room wasn't either.</i>

1901
01:43:04,053 --> 01:43:06,429
<i>After gaining access to the warehouse,</i>

1902
01:43:06,639 --> 01:43:08,723
<i>The Horsemen left the real safe</i>

1903
01:43:08,807 --> 01:43:13,770
<i>and transformed the whole room</i>
into a giant rabbit box.

1904
01:43:15,397 --> 01:43:20,234
<i>You go charging in there,</i>
thinking the safe was already gone.

1905
01:43:20,444 --> 01:43:21,444
Hey!

1906
01:43:21,528 --> 01:43:22,820
Hey! Stop!

1907
01:43:23,030 --> 01:43:24,280
Missing the trick. Again.

1908
01:43:24,365 --> 01:43:27,533
Which was to make you think
the safe had already been stolen,

1909
01:43:27,618 --> 01:43:29,702
so you'd drop your guard and leave.

1910
01:43:30,245 --> 01:43:33,206
<i>Now, while you were busy</i>
playing with balloon animals,

1911
01:43:33,415 --> 01:43:36,000
<i>someone was breaking into the warehouse.</i>

1912
01:43:54,520 --> 01:43:55,687
Who?

1913
01:43:57,106 --> 01:43:58,606
<i>Jack Wilder.</i>

1914
01:43:59,358 --> 01:44:00,692
Holy shit.

1915
01:44:00,901 --> 01:44:03,277
No. No way. He died right in front of my eyes.

1916
01:44:04,071 --> 01:44:06,155
Unless, of course, he didn't.

1917
01:44:13,497 --> 01:44:14,789
It's locked.

1918
01:44:15,582 --> 01:44:16,791
JACK: Weren't you listening?

1919
01:44:17,292 --> 01:44:18,334
Nothing's ever locked.

1920
01:44:18,502 --> 01:44:19,585
MERRITT: Ah!

1921
01:44:19,753 --> 01:44:22,338
Well done, Mr. Wilder! Good work.

1922
01:44:22,423 --> 01:44:24,382
MERRITT: You're a big boy now, Jack.

1923
01:44:24,466 --> 01:44:26,843
He escaped in a standard FBI vehicle, right?

1924
01:44:30,889 --> 01:44:32,223
<i>Led you to the bridge.</i>

1925
01:44:32,474 --> 01:44:36,102
<i>Where the other Horsemen were waiting</i>
with an identical replacement car.

1926
01:44:37,104 --> 01:44:39,188
<i>It only took a split second</i>
for you to lose contact with it

1927
01:44:39,273 --> 01:44:40,273
<i>and make the switch.</i>

1928
01:44:50,200 --> 01:44:51,284
(MERRITT LAUGHS)

1929
01:44:53,537 --> 01:44:54,954
- Oh!
- (LAUGHS)

1930
01:45:02,588 --> 01:45:05,590
<i>THADDEUS: When you crawled</i>
into that burning car,

1931
01:45:05,966 --> 01:45:07,967
<i>quite heroically, I might add,</i>

1932
01:45:09,845 --> 01:45:11,929
<i>you almost died trying to rescue</i>

1933
01:45:12,014 --> 01:45:15,016
<i>what I assume was a cadaver</i>
from the morgue.

1934
01:45:16,518 --> 01:45:20,188
<i>DYLAN: Why go through such an elaborate</i>
and dangerous plan

1935
01:45:21,065 --> 01:45:23,274
- just to frame one guy?
- I don't know.

1936
01:45:23,358 --> 01:45:25,359
They never kept any of the money they took.

1937
01:45:25,444 --> 01:45:27,820
Yeah, that's the part
I haven't been able to put together yet.

1938
01:45:27,905 --> 01:45:30,490
But I just gave you information that
is substantially more important.

1939
01:45:30,574 --> 01:45:32,450
- No. Not really.
- What?

1940
01:45:32,534 --> 01:45:36,871
I finally got a chance to really look into
Lionel Shrike.

1941
01:45:37,289 --> 01:45:40,124
His comeback attempt. His accident.

1942
01:45:41,085 --> 01:45:44,587
The insurer who denied the family's claim?

1943
01:45:44,838 --> 01:45:46,047
Tressler Insurance.

1944
01:45:47,966 --> 01:45:50,218
The bank that carried the note?

1945
01:45:51,261 --> 01:45:52,845
Credit Republican of Paris.

1946
01:45:52,930 --> 01:45:54,514
Credit Republicain de Paris.

1947
01:45:56,141 --> 01:45:57,433
DYLAN: What do you make of that?

1948
01:45:57,643 --> 01:45:59,602
A sucker is born every minute.

1949
01:46:00,562 --> 01:46:05,817
What if all this was just leading up to us
getting mugged in Central Park at 2:00 a. M?

1950
01:46:05,901 --> 01:46:08,069
No, I'm telling you,
we're right where we need to be.

1951
01:46:08,821 --> 01:46:11,072
- We just have to find...
- That?

1952
01:46:13,617 --> 01:46:15,368
DANIEL: The Lionel Shrike tree.

1953
01:46:16,120 --> 01:46:18,121
HENLEY: And the card encased in glass.

1954
01:46:20,165 --> 01:46:21,624
What do we do now?

1955
01:46:38,433 --> 01:46:39,892
Oh, nice!

1956
01:46:41,687 --> 01:46:43,855
(CAROUSEL MUSIC PLAYING)

1957
01:46:55,868 --> 01:46:57,326
<i>DYLAN: So, here's my new theory.</i>

1958
01:46:57,661 --> 01:47:01,122
The legend is that the "Eye" is everywhere.

1959
01:47:01,790 --> 01:47:02,957
Waiting

1960
01:47:03,333 --> 01:47:07,128
for the truly great magicians
to distinguish themselves

1961
01:47:08,088 --> 01:47:09,839
from the mediocre ones.

1962
01:47:10,591 --> 01:47:11,841
Maybe that was you.

1963
01:47:12,551 --> 01:47:14,802
Deep down inside you wanted nothing more

1964
01:47:14,887 --> 01:47:17,263
than to be part of the "Eye,"
but you were never invited.

1965
01:47:17,598 --> 01:47:20,683
So you try to destroy them.
But instead what happens?

1966
01:47:21,226 --> 01:47:22,685
You pissed them off.

1967
01:47:24,438 --> 01:47:27,440
The Eye isn't real.

1968
01:47:27,524 --> 01:47:30,610
Okay, then, explain then.
Who's behind all this.

1969
01:47:31,069 --> 01:47:32,653
Somebody with an obsession.

1970
01:47:32,738 --> 01:47:33,905
- Meticulous.
- Who?

1971
01:47:33,989 --> 01:47:37,158
Somebody prepared to sacrifice everything.

1972
01:47:37,242 --> 01:47:41,454
Somebody so prepared to lose
that they wouldn't even be a suspect

1973
01:47:41,538 --> 01:47:42,580
until the trick was done.

1974
01:47:42,664 --> 01:47:45,374
I don't want a profile. I need a name.
Who? Who?

1975
01:47:45,459 --> 01:47:47,168
I don't know who.

1976
01:47:47,628 --> 01:47:51,130
But they had to have access to the warehouse
to plant the mirrors.

1977
01:47:52,549 --> 01:47:56,469
Always a step ahead of me. And the FBI.

1978
01:47:56,553 --> 01:47:59,805
Got past them not once,
not twice, but consistently.

1979
01:48:00,224 --> 01:48:02,225
Almost as if they were on the in...

1980
01:48:15,614 --> 01:48:16,822
DYLAN: (WHISPERING) The inside.

1981
01:48:29,127 --> 01:48:31,504
- You.
- Mmm.

1982
01:48:34,758 --> 01:48:35,925
Why?

1983
01:48:36,593 --> 01:48:38,719
That is the question, isn't it?

1984
01:48:39,763 --> 01:48:40,846
You're right.

1985
01:48:41,932 --> 01:48:46,352
I can't tell you how long I've waited
to see the look on your face.

1986
01:48:48,814 --> 01:48:50,147
Who are you?

1987
01:48:51,400 --> 01:48:52,775
What do you want from me?

1988
01:48:53,652 --> 01:48:55,152
What do I want?

1989
01:48:55,570 --> 01:48:58,489
I want you to spend
the rest of your life in this cell,

1990
01:48:58,573 --> 01:49:02,576
staring at four walls
and wondering how you missed it.

1991
01:49:03,287 --> 01:49:06,372
How you let yourself
be so blinded by your ego

1992
01:49:06,915 --> 01:49:09,333
that you convinced yourself
that you were one step ahead

1993
01:49:09,418 --> 01:49:11,752
when you were always two steps behind.

1994
01:49:16,800 --> 01:49:17,925
Dylan?

1995
01:49:19,011 --> 01:49:20,011
Wait a minute.

1996
01:49:21,054 --> 01:49:22,972
Dylan! How did this happen?

1997
01:49:25,767 --> 01:49:26,767
(AUDIENCE CHEERING)

1998
01:49:28,478 --> 01:49:29,687
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

1999
01:49:30,856 --> 01:49:32,523
Dylan!

2000
01:49:32,691 --> 01:49:35,151
Why?

2001
01:49:39,448 --> 01:49:41,532
- MERRITT: Oh, my God.
- (JACK CHUCKLING)

2002
01:49:42,576 --> 01:49:45,745
I did not see that coming. That's impossible!

2003
01:49:45,829 --> 01:49:46,871
JACK: No way.

2004
01:49:46,955 --> 01:49:49,373
That was actually pretty good.

2005
01:49:49,791 --> 01:49:50,833
Thank you.

2006
01:49:51,293 --> 01:49:53,586
When I said,
"Always be the smartest guy in the room."

2007
01:49:53,670 --> 01:49:54,628
We were in agreement.

2008
01:49:54,713 --> 01:49:55,755
Okay. Right.

2009
01:49:56,423 --> 01:49:57,423
Henley.

2010
01:49:58,175 --> 01:49:59,884
I've never seen her speechless.

2011
01:50:00,010 --> 01:50:01,719
I take that as a huge compliment.

2012
01:50:02,429 --> 01:50:05,097
Hey, man, I'm so sorry for kicking your ass.
Really.

2013
01:50:05,932 --> 01:50:11,145
Hey, listen, for the record,
I have always been a 100% believer.

2014
01:50:11,229 --> 01:50:14,482
And the amount of energy I have expended
to keep these infidels on point...

2015
01:50:14,566 --> 01:50:15,691
(HENLEY LAUGHING)

2016
01:50:15,776 --> 01:50:17,818
Merritt, you're in.

2017
01:50:18,653 --> 01:50:19,695
God bless.

2018
01:50:19,821 --> 01:50:20,863
DYLAN: Come.

2019
01:50:21,907 --> 01:50:26,994
The real magic is taking four strong solo acts
and making them all work together.

2020
01:50:27,079 --> 01:50:29,246
And that's exactly what you did.

2021
01:50:30,665 --> 01:50:31,707
So welcome.

2022
01:50:35,045 --> 01:50:37,129
Welcome to the Eye.

2023
01:50:39,424 --> 01:50:40,549
(HENLEY GASPS)

2024
01:51:44,281 --> 01:51:45,781
It was all connected.

2025
01:51:47,033 --> 01:51:50,035
Credit Republican. Tressler Insurance.

2026
01:51:52,205 --> 01:51:56,292
<i>Bonjour.</i>

2027
01:51:59,421 --> 01:52:02,756
And Elkhorn?
What's the connection to Shrike?

2028
01:52:05,343 --> 01:52:10,890
Elkhorn started as a safe manufacturer.
They used cheap steel.

2029
01:52:12,476 --> 01:52:13,517
They cut corners.

2030
01:52:13,852 --> 01:52:16,979
When he got to the bottom of the river,
the safe warped.

2031
01:52:17,063 --> 01:52:18,439
And he was trapped.

2032
01:52:20,066 --> 01:52:21,692
He was your father.

2033
01:52:23,612 --> 01:52:26,947
<i>DYLAN: The morning before the show</i>
didn't feel like any other day.

2034
01:52:27,991 --> 01:52:32,995
<i>When my father said he had to go to work,</i>
he could see that I didn't want him to leave.

2035
01:52:35,290 --> 01:52:40,419
<i>So he gave me his watch, and he told me</i>
to count the seconds until he came back.

2036
01:52:41,588 --> 01:52:44,256
<i>I have never let his watch stop since then.</i>

2037
01:52:44,341 --> 01:52:46,467
And from that moment on,

2038
01:52:46,551 --> 01:52:49,136
I created a persona.

2039
01:52:49,763 --> 01:52:51,639
I planned. I worked out every detail.

2040
01:52:51,723 --> 01:52:55,017
But the one thing
that I couldn't imagine happening

2041
01:52:55,477 --> 01:52:56,644
was you.

2042
01:52:58,313 --> 01:53:01,273
And I know that the logical conclusion for you

2043
01:53:01,775 --> 01:53:04,485
is to take this case to its resolution.

2044
01:53:04,569 --> 01:53:07,655
And for you to turn me in.

2045
01:53:12,744 --> 01:53:13,827
Yeah.

2046
01:53:15,789 --> 01:53:19,625
But you know how I feel
about resolution and logic.

2047
01:53:21,002 --> 01:53:22,336
And you also know

2048
01:53:23,171 --> 01:53:27,508
that I think some things
are best left unexplained.

2049
01:53:34,015 --> 01:53:35,724
DYLAN: One more secret to lock away.

2050
01:53:36,434 --> 01:53:37,893
(ALMA CHUCKLES)

2051
01:53:40,480 --> 01:53:42,022
- Hmm.
- (LAUGHS)

2052
01:54:03,295 --> 01:54:04,545
DYLAN: Come in close.

2053
01:54:05,297 --> 01:54:06,463
<i>Closer.</i>

2054
01:54:06,798 --> 01:54:08,757
DANIEL: Because nowyou know oursecret.

2055
01:54:09,009 --> 01:54:11,385
<i>MERRITT: We could be anywhere.</i>
Watching you.

2056
01:54:11,928 --> 01:54:14,805
<i>HENLEY: We're looking forsomeone</i>
to help us with our next trick.

2057
01:54:15,640 --> 01:54:18,183
<i>JACK: On the count of three, open your eyes</i>

2058
01:54:18,268 --> 01:54:19,893
<i>and tell me what you see.</i>

2059
01:54:21,229 --> 01:54:22,313
DYLAN: One.

2060
01:54:22,439 --> 01:54:23,480
Two...

2061
01:55:55,365 --> 01:55:57,241
DANIEL: Please, stop, stop, stop.

2062
01:55:57,659 --> 01:56:01,328
All right, stop the van. Stop the van.
I'm gonna jump out of the van.

2063
01:56:02,330 --> 01:56:03,831
Oh, thank God.

2064
01:56:05,750 --> 01:56:07,835
HENLEY: Where are we?

2065
01:56:07,919 --> 01:56:10,337
Great, another shit hole.

2066
01:56:10,421 --> 01:56:12,381
Okay, feeling it.

2067
01:56:12,465 --> 01:56:16,635
I'm exhausted, and hungry, and cranky.

2068
01:56:17,679 --> 01:56:19,513
HENLEY: Check out this place.

2069
01:56:19,597 --> 01:56:20,931
MERRITT: Where'd you bring us?

2070
01:56:21,057 --> 01:56:22,432
DANIEL: Was there no landfill where we were?

2071
01:56:22,517 --> 01:56:24,351
JACK: This place is awesome.

2072
01:56:25,895 --> 01:56:27,604
- Is this our new gear?
- DANIEL: There'd better not be, like,

2073
01:56:27,689 --> 01:56:29,648
matching jumpsuits in there.
You know I don't wear spandex.

2074
01:56:29,732 --> 01:56:30,858
It's locked.

2075
01:56:31,025 --> 01:56:32,109
Guys, the cards.

2076
01:56:32,193 --> 01:56:33,402
What card?

2077
01:56:33,528 --> 01:56:34,736
DANIEL: What do you mean, "what card"?

2078
01:56:36,823 --> 01:56:37,823
Hmm.

2079
01:56:38,867 --> 01:56:39,867
Okay.

2080
01:56:40,160 --> 01:56:41,994
(UPBEAT SONG PLAYING)

2081
02:00:31,849 --> 02:00:33,600
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

